# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: algol-family
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:algol-family/algol-60] Niklaus Wirth based his own ALGOL W on ALGOL 60 before moving to develop Pascal.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] Algol-W was intended to be the next generation ALGOL but the ALGOL 68 committee decided on a design that was more complex and advanced rather than a cleaned simplified ALGOL 60.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] The official ALGOL versions are named after the year they were first published.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] ALGOL 68 is substantially different from ALGOL 60 and was criticised partially for being so, so that in general "ALGOL" refers to dialects of ALGOL 60.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] ALGOL 60 – with COBOL – were the first languages to seek standardization.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] ALGOL 60 was used mostly by research computer scientists in the United States and in Europe.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] Its use in commercial applications was hindered by the absence of standard input/output facilities in its description and the lack of interest in the language by large computer vendors.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] ALGOL 60 did however become the standard for the publication of algorithms and had a profound effect on future language development.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] John Backus developed the Backus normal form method of describing programming languages specifically for ALGOL 58.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] It was revised and expanded by Peter Naur for ALGOL 60, and at Donald Knuth's suggestion renamed Backus–Naur form.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] Peter Naur: "As editor of the ALGOL Bulletin I was drawn into the international discussions of the language and was selected to be member of the European language design group in November 1959.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] Alan Perlis gave a vivid description of the meeting: "The meetings were exhausting, interminable, and exhilarating.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] One became aggravated when one's good ideas were discarded along with the bad ones of others.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] Nevertheless, diligence persisted during the entire period.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] The language originally did not include recursion.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] It was inserted into the specification at the last minute, against the wishes of some of the committee.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] Several authors of the original report met in April 1962 to resolve issues that had arisen.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] Their work resulted in the publication of the "Revised report on the algorithmic language ALGOL 60".
[src:algol-family/algol-60] Further clarifications and the inclusion of I/O procedures were made by the Working Group 2.1 of IFIP Technical Committee 2.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] These efforts were published as the "Modified Report on the algorithmic language ALGOL 60" in 1975.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] ALGOL 60 inspired many languages that followed it.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] To date there have been at least 70 augmentations, extensions, derivations and sublanguages of ALGOL 60.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] The Burroughs dialects included special system programming dialects such as ESPOL and NEWP.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] ALGOL 60 as officially defined had no I/O facilities; implementations defined their own in ways that were rarely compatible with each other.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] In contrast, ALGOL 68 offered an extensive library of *transput* (ALGOL 68 parlance for input/output) facilities.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] ALGOL 60 provided two evaluation strategies for parameter passing: the common call-by-value, and call-by-name.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] The procedure declaration specified, for each formal parameter, which was to be used: *value* specified for call-by-value, and omitted for call-by-name.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] Call-by-name recomputes every parameter when it is used in an expression, so has certain effects in contrast to call-by-reference.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] For example, without specifying the parameters as *value* or *reference*, it is impossible to develop a procedure that will swap the values of two parameters if the actual parameters that are passed in are an integer variable and an array that is indexed by that same integer variable.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] Think of passing a pointer to swap(i, A[i]) in to a function.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] Now that every time swap is referenced, it's reevaluated.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] Say i := 1 and A[i] := 2, so every time swap is referenced it'll return the other combination of the values ([1,2], [2,1], [1,2] and so on).
[src:algol-family/algol-60] A similar situation occurs with a random function passed as actual argument.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] Call-by-name is known by many compiler designers for the interesting "thunks" that are used to implement it.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] Donald Knuth devised the "man or boy test" to separate compilers that correctly implemented "recursion and non-local references." This test contains an example of call-by-name.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] The ALGOL 60 reports recognize three different levels of language, i.e., a Reference Language, a Publication Language, and several Hardware Representations.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] The Reference and Publication languages have no reserved words, however the reports do recommend reserving some identifiers for standard functions.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] The Reference Language has lower case letters and other characters not available in the 6-bit character sets typical of ALGOL 60's era.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] The reports briefly describe hardware representations.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] Implementations differ in their hardware representations of underlined independent basic symbols.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] They also differ in their hardware representation of delimiters.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] There are 24 basic symbols in the Modified Report that are words in boldface.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] Although those words are not reserved in the reference and publication languages, some hardware implementations may reserve them.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] and also the names of all the intrinsic functions.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] Implementations differ in how the text in bold must be written.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] For example, the word 'INTEGER', including the quotation marks, must be used in some implementations in place of **integer**, above, thereby designating it as a special ALGOL symbol.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] The following version uses the hardware representation supported by the ALCOR compiler for the IBM 7090.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] Additionally, it uses `..` to represent the colon character, `.=` for assignment, `(/ and )/` instead of brackets, and `.,` for semicolon.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] Since ALGOL 60 had no I/O facilities, there is no portable hello world program in ALGOL.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] The following program could (and still will) compile and run on an ALGOL implementation for a Unisys A-Series mainframe, and is a straightforward simplification of code taken from The Language Guide at the University of Michigan-Dearborn Computer and Information Science Department Hello world!
[src:algol-family/algol-60] Where * etc. represented a format specification as used in FORTRAN, e.g.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] An alternative example, using Elliott Algol I/O is as follows.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] Elliott Algol used different characters for "open-string-quote" and "close-string-quote", represented here by ‘ and ’ .
[src:algol-family/algol-60] Here's a version for the Elliott 803 Algol (A104) The standard Elliott 803 used 5-hole paper tape and thus only had upper case.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] The code lacked any quote characters so £ (pound sign) was used for open quote and ?
[src:algol-family/algol-60] Special sequences were placed in double quotes (e.g£., L?? produced a new line on the teleprinter).
[src:algol-family/algol-60] The ICT 1900 series Algol I/O version allowed input from paper tape or punched card.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] Paper tape 'full' mode allowed lower case.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] LEAP is an extension to the ALGOL 60 programming language which provides an associative memory of triples.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] The three items in a triple denote the association that an Attribute of an Object has a specific Value.
[src:algol-family/algol-60] LEAP was created by Jerome Feldman (University of California Berkeley) and Paul Rovner (MIT Lincoln Lab) in 1967.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] The complexity of the language's definition, which runs to several hundred pages filled with non-standard terminology, made compiler implementation difficult and it was said it had "no implementations and no users".
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] This was only partly true; ALGOL 68 did find use in several niche markets, notably in the United Kingdom where it was popular on International Computers Limited (ICL) machines, and in teaching roles.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Outside these fields, use was relatively limited.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Nevertheless, the contributions of ALGOL 68 to the field of computer science have been deep, wide-ranging and enduring, although many of these contributions were only publicly identified when they had reappeared in subsequently developed programming languages.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Many languages were developed specifically as a response to the perceived complexity of the language, the most notable being Pascal, or were reimplementations for specific roles, like Ada.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Many languages of the 1970s trace their design specifically to ALGOL 68, selecting some features while abandoning others that were considered too complex or out-of-scope for given roles.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Most modern languages trace at least some of their syntax to either C or Pascal, and thus directly or indirectly to ALGOL 68.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] ALGOL 68 features include expression-based syntax, user-declared types and structures/tagged-unions, a reference model of variables and reference parameters, string, array and matrix slicing, and concurrency.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] ALGOL 68 was designed by the International Federation for Information Processing (IFIP) IFIP Working Group 2.1 on Algorithmic Languages and Calculi.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] On 20 December 1968, the language was formally adopted by the group, and then approved for publication by the General Assembly of IFIP.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] ALGOL 68 was defined using a formalism, a two-level formal grammar, invented by Adriaan van Wijngaarden.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] ALGOL 68 has been criticized, most prominently by some members of its design committee such as C.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Hoare and Edsger Dijkstra, for abandoning the simplicity of ALGOL 60, becoming a vehicle for complex or overly general ideas, and doing little to make the compiler writer's task easier, in contrast to deliberately simple contemporaries (and competitors) such as C, S-algol and Pascal.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] In 1970, ALGOL 68-R became the first working compiler for ALGOL 68.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] In the 1973 revision, certain features — such as proceduring, gommas and formal bounds — were omitted.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] ALGOL 68 also had a notable influence in the Soviet Union, details of which can be found in Andrey Terekhov's 2014 paper: "ALGOL 68 and Its Impact on the USSR and Russian Programming", and "Алгол 68 и его влияние на программирование в СССР и России".
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Steve Bourne, who was on the ALGOL 68 revision committee, took some of its ideas to his Bourne shell (and thereby, to descendant Unix shells such as Bash) and to C (and thereby to descendants such as C++).
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] The source of Bourne shell, while written in C, uses macros to make it look more like ALGOL.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] The complete history of the project can be found in C.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] For a full-length treatment of the language, see "Programming ALGOL 68 Made Easy" by Dr.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Sian Mountbatten, or "Learning ALGOL 68 Genie" by Marcel van der Veer which includes the Revised Report.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] ALGOL 68, as the name implies, is a follow-on to the ALGOL language that was first formalized in 1960.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] That same year the International Federation for Information Processing (IFIP) formed and started the Working Group on ALGOL, or WG2.1.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] This group released an updated ALGOL 60 specification in Rome in April 1962.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] At a follow-up meeting in March 1964, it was agreed that the group should begin work on two follow-on standards, ALGOL X, which would be a redefinition of the language with some additions, and ALGOL Y, which would have the ability to modify its own programs in the style of the language LISP.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] The first meeting of the ALGOL X group was held in Princeton University in May 1965.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] A report of the meeting noted two broadly supported themes, the introduction of strong typing and interest in Euler's concepts of 'trees' or 'lists' for handling collections.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Although intended as a "short-term solution to existing difficulties", ALGOL X got as far as having a compiler made for it.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Ross of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) with the *Automated Engineering Design* (AED-0) system, also termed *ALGOL Extended for Design*.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] At the second meeting in October in France, three formal proposals were presented, Niklaus Wirth's ALGOL W along with comments about record structures by C.A.R.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] (Tony) Hoare, a similar language by Gerhard Seegmüller, and a paper by Adriaan van Wijngaarden on "Orthogonal design and description of a formal language".
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] The latter, written in almost indecipherable "W-Grammar", proved to be a decisive shift in the evolution of the language.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] The meeting closed with an agreement that van Wijngaarden would re-write the Wirth/Hoare submission using his W-Grammar.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] This seemingly simple task ultimately proved more difficult than expected, and the follow-up meeting had to be delayed six months.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] When it met in April 1966 in Kootwijk, van Wijngaarden's draft remained incomplete and Wirth and Hoare presented a version using more traditional descriptions.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] It was generally agreed that their paper was "the right language in the wrong formalism".
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] As these approaches were explored, it became clear there was a difference in the way parameters were described that would have real-world effects, and while Wirth and Hoare protested that further delays might become endless, the committee decided to wait for van Wijngaarden's version.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Wirth then implemented their current definition as ALGOL W.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] At the next meeting in Warsaw in October 1966, there was an initial report from the I/O Subcommittee who had met at the Oak Ridge National Laboratory and the University of Illinois but had not yet made much progress.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] The two proposals from the previous meeting were again explored, and this time a new debate emerged about the use of pointers; ALGOL W used them only to refer to records, while van Wijngaarden's version could point to any object.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] To add confusion, John McCarthy presented a new proposal for operator overloading and the ability to string together *and* and *or* constructs, and Klaus Samelson wanted to allow anonymous functions.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] In the resulting confusion, there was some discussion of abandoning the entire effort.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] The confusion continued through what was supposed to be the ALGOL Y meeting in Zandvoort in May 1967.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] A draft report was finally published in February 1968.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] This was met by "shock, horror and dissent", mostly due to the hundreds of pages of unreadable grammar and odd terminology.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Lindsey attempted to figure out what "language was hidden inside of it", a process that took six man-weeks of effort.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] The resulting paper, "ALGOL 68 with fewer tears", was widely circulated.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] At a wider information processing meeting in Zürich in May 1968, attendees complained that the language was being forced upon them and that IFIP was "the true villain of this unreasonable situation" as the meetings were mostly closed and there was no formal feedback mechanism.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Wirth and Peter Naur formally resigned their authorship positions in WG2.1 at that time.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] The next WG2.1 meeting took place in Tirrenia in June 1968.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] It was supposed to discuss the release of compilers and other issues, but instead devolved into a discussion on the language. van Wijngaarden responded by saying (or threatening) that he would release only one more version of the report.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] By this point Naur, Hoare, and Wirth had left the effort, and several more were threatening to do so.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Several more meetings followed, North Berwick in August 1968, Munich in December which produced the release of the official Report in January 1969 but also resulted in a contentious Minority Report being written.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Finally, at Banff, Alberta in September 1969, the project was generally considered complete and the discussion was primarily on errata and a greatly expanded Introduction to the Report.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] The effort took five years, burned out many of the greatest names in computer science, and on several occasions became deadlocked over issues both in the definition and the group as a whole.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Hoare released a "Critique of ALGOL 68" almost immediately, which has been widely referenced in many works.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Wirth went on to further develop the ALGOL W concept and released this as Pascal in 1970.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] The first implementation of the standard, based on the late-1968 draft Report, was introduced by the Royal Radar Establishment in the UK as ALGOL 68-R in July 1970.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] This was, however, a subset of the full language, and Barry Mailloux, the final editor of the Report, joked that "It is a question of morality.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] We have a Bible and you are sinning!" This version nevertheless became very popular on the ICL machines, and became a widely used language in military coding, especially in the UK.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Among the changes in 68-R was the requirement for all variables to be declared before their first use.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] This had a significant advantage that it allowed the compiler to be one-pass, as space for the variables in the activation record was set aside before it was used.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] However, this change also had the side-effect of demanding the **PROC**s be declared twice, once as a declaration of the types, and then again as the body of code.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Another change was to eliminate the assumed **VOID** mode, an expression that returns no value (named a *statement* in other languages) and demanding the word **VOID** be added where it would have been assumed.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Further, 68-R eliminated the explicit parallel processing commands based on **PAR**.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] The first full implementation of the language was introduced in 1974 by CDC Netherlands for the Control Data mainframe series.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] This saw limited use, mostly teaching in Germany and the Netherlands.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] A version similar to 68-R was introduced from Carnegie Mellon University in 1976 as 68S, and was again a one-pass compiler based on various simplifications of the original and intended for use on smaller machines like the DEC PDP-11.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] It too was used mostly for teaching purposes.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] A version for IBM mainframes did not become available until 1978, when one was released from Cambridge University.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Lindsey released a version for small machines including the IBM PC in 1984.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] 1968: On 20 December 1968, the "Final Report" (MR 101) was adopted by the Working Group, then subsequently approved by the General Assembly of UNESCO's IFIP for publication.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Translations of the standard were made for Russian, German, French and Bulgarian, and then later Japanese and Chinese.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] The standard was also made available in Braille.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] 1988: Subsequently ALGOL 68 became one of the GOST standards in Russia.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] The basic language construct is the *unit*.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] A unit may be a *formula*, an *enclosed clause*, a *routine text* or one of several technically needed constructs (assignation, jump, skip, nihil).
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] The technical term *enclosed clause* unifies some of the inherently bracketing constructs known as *block*, *do statement*, *switch statement* in other contemporary languages.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] When keywords are used, generally the reversed character sequence of the introducing keyword is used for terminating the enclosure, e.g.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] This Guarded Command syntax was reused by Stephen Bourne in the common Unix Bourne shell.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] An expression may also yield a *multiple value*, which is constructed from other values by a *collateral clause*.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] This construct just looks like the parameter pack of a procedure call.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] The basic data types (called `mode`s in Algol 68 parlance) are `real`, `int`, `compl` (complex number), `bool`, `char`, `bits` and `bytes`.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] However, the declaration `**REAL** x;` is just syntactic sugar for `**REF** **REAL** x = **LOC** **REAL**;`.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] That is, `x` is really the *constant identifier* for a *reference to* a newly generated local **REAL** variable.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Furthermore, instead of defining both `float` and `double`, or `int` and `long` and `short`, etc., ALGOL 68 provides *modifiers*, so that the presently common `double` would be written as **LONG** **REAL** or **LONG** **LONG** **REAL** instead, for example.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] The *prelude constants* `max real` and `min long int` are provided to adapt programs to different implementations.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] All variables need to be declared, but declaration does not have to precede the first use.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] For ALGOL 68, only the **NEWMODE** mode-indication appears to the left of the equals symbol, and most notably the construction is made, and can be read, from left to right without regard to priorities.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Also, the **lower bound** of Algol 68 arrays is one by default, but can be any integer from -*max int* to *max int*.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Mode declarations allow types to be recursive: defined directly or indirectly in terms of themselves.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] The coercions produce a coercee from a coercend according to three criteria: the a priori mode of the coercend before the application of any coercion, the a posteriori mode of the coercee required after those coercions, and the syntactic position or "sort" of the coercee.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] The six possible coercions are termed *deproceduring*, *dereferencing*, *uniting*, *widening*, *rowing*, and *voiding*.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Each coercion, except for *uniting*, prescribes a corresponding dynamic effect on the associated values.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Hence, many primitive actions can be programmed implicitly by coercions.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] ALGOL 68 has a hierarchy of contexts which determine the kind of coercions available at a particular point in the program.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] For more details about Primaries, Secondaries, Tertiary & Quaternaries refer to Operator precedence.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Pragmats (from "pragmatic remarks") are directives in the program, typically hints to the compiler; in newer languages these are called "pragmas" (no 't'). e.g.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Normally, comments cannot be nested in ALGOL 68.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] This restriction can be circumvented by using different comment delimiters (e.g. use hash only for temporary code deletions).
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] ALGOL 68 being an expression-oriented programming language, the value returned by an assignment statement is a reference to the destination.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] This notion is present in C and Perl, among others.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Note that as in earlier languages such as Algol 60 and FORTRAN, spaces are allowed in identifiers, so that `half pi` is a *single* identifier (thus avoiding the *underscores* versus *camel case* versus *all lower-case* issues).
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Note that, being an integer expression, the former block of code can be used in *any context where an integer value can be used*.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] A block of code returns the value of the last expression it evaluated; this idea is present in Lisp, among other languages.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] This scheme not only avoids the dangling else problem but also avoids having to use `**BEGIN**` and `**END**` in embedded statement sequences.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Algol68 allowed the switch to be of either type **INT** *or* (uniquely) **UNION**.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] The latter allows the enforcing strong typing onto **UNION** variables. cf.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Subsequent "extensions" to the standard Algol68 allowed the **TO** syntactic element to be replaced with **UPTO** and **DOWNTO** to achieve a small optimisation.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Further examples can be found in the code examples below.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] ALGOL 68 supports arrays with any number of dimensions, and it allows for the *slicing* of whole or partial rows or columns.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] ALGOL 68 supports multiple field structures (**STRUCT**) and **united modes**.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Reference variables may point to any **MODE** including array slices and structure fields.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] The return value of a `proc` is the value of the last expression evaluated in the procedure.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] References to procedures (**ref proc**) are also permitted.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Call-by-reference parameters are provided by specifying references (such as `**ref real**`) in the formal argument list.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] This simplicity of code was unachievable in ALGOL 68's predecessor ALGOL 60.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] The programmer may define new **operators** and *both* those and the pre-defined ones may be overloaded and their priorities may be changed by the coder.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] The following example defines operator `**MAX**` with both dyadic and monadic versions (scanning across the elements of an array).
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Note: Quaternaries include names **SKIP** and ~.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] `:=:` (alternatively **IS**) tests if two pointers are equal; `:/=:` (alternatively **ISNT**) tests if they are unequal.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Now consider how to decide whether these two are pointing to the same location, or whether one of them is pointing to **NIL**.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] will dereference both pointers down to values of type **INT**, and compare those, since the = operator is defined for **INT**, but not **REF** **INT**.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] It is *not legal* to define = for operands of type **REF** **INT** and **INT** at the same time, because then calls become ambiguous, due to the implicit coercions that can be applied: should the operands be left as **REF** **INT** and that version of the operator called?
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Or should they be dereferenced further to **INT** and that version used instead?
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Hence the need for separate constructs not subject to the normal coercion rules for operands to operators.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] while legal, will probably not do what might be expected.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] They will always return **FALSE**, because they are comparing the *actual addresses of the variables*`ip`*and*`jp`*, rather than what they point to*.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Most of Algol's "special" characters (⊂, ≡, ␣, ×, ÷, ≤, ≥, ≠, ¬, ⊃, ≡, ∨, ∧, →, ↓, ↑, ⌊, ⌈, ⎩, ⎧, ⊥, ⏨, ¢, ○ and □) can be found on the IBM 2741 keyboard with the APL "golf-ball" print head inserted; these became available in the mid-1960s while ALGOL 68 was being drafted.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] These characters are also part of the Unicode standard and most of them are available in several popular fonts.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Note the predefined procedures `newpage` and `newline` passed as arguments.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] "Formatted transput" in ALGOL 68's transput has its own syntax and patterns (functions), with **FORMAT**s embedded between two $ characters.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] The term **NIL** **IS** *var* always evaluates to **TRUE** for any variable (but see above for correct use of **IS** :/=:), whereas it is not known to which value a comparison *x* < **SKIP** evaluates for any integer *x*.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] ALGOL 68 leaves intentionally undefined what happens in case of integer overflow, the integer bit representation, and the degree of numerical accuracy for floating point.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Both official reports included some advanced features that were not part of the standard language.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] These were indicated with an ℵ and considered effectively private.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] This sample program implements the Sieve of Eratosthenes to find all the prime numbers that are less than 100.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] **NIL** is the ALGOL 68 analogue of the *null pointer* in other languages.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] The notation *x* **OF** *y* accesses a member *x* of a **STRUCT** *y*.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p01] Both ALGOL 68C and ALGOL 68-R are written in ALGOL 68, effectively making ALGOL 68 an application of itself.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] A feature of ALGOL 68, inherited from the ALGOL tradition, is its different representations.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] Programs in the *strict language* (which is rigorously defined in the Report) denote production trees in the form of a sequence of grammar symbols, and should be represented using some *representation language*, of which there are many and tailored to different purposes.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] The Revised Report defines a *reference language* and it is recommended for representation languages that are intended to be read by humans to be close enough to the reference language so symbols can be distinguished "without further elucidation".
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] These representation languages are called *implementations of the reference language*.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] For example, the construct in the strict language **bold-begin-symbol** could be represented as **begin** in a publication language, as *BEGIN* in a programming language or as the bytes 0xC000 in some hardware language.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] Similarly, the strict language **differs from symbol** could be represented as ≠ or as /=.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] The programmer who writes executable code does not always have an option of **BOLD** typeface or underlining in the code as this may depend on hardware and cultural issues.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] Different methods to denote these identifiers have been devised.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] All implementations must recognize at least POINT, UPPER and RES inside PRAGMAT sections.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] Of these, POINT and UPPER stropping are quite common.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] QUOTE (single apostrophe quoting) was the original recommendation.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] It may seem that RES stropping is a contradiction to the specification, as there are no reserved words in Algol 68.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] In RES stropping the representation of the bold word (or keyword) **begin** is *begin*, and the representation of the identifier *begin* is *begin_*.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] Note that the underscore character is just a representation artifact and not part of the represented identifier.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] In contrast, in non-stropped languages with reserved words, like for example C, it is not possible to represent an identifier *if*, since the representation *if_* represents the identifier *if_*, not *if*.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] ALGOL 68 allows for every natural language to define its own set of keywords Algol-68.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] As a result, programmers are able to write programs using keywords from their native language.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] Below is an example of a simple procedure that calculates "the day following", the code is in two languages: English and German.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] Except where noted (with a superscript), the language described above is that of the "Revised Report(r1)".
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] The original language (As per the "Final Report"r0) differs in syntax of the *mode cast*, and it had the feature of *proceduring*, i.e. coercing the value of a term into a procedure which evaluates the term.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] Proceduring would be intended to make evaluations *lazy*.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] The most useful application could have been the short-circuited evaluation of Boolean operators.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] against the programmers naïve expectations the print *would* be executed as it is only the *value* of the elaborated enclosed-clause after **ANDF** that was procedured.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] Textual insertion of the commented-out **PROC** **BOOL**: makes it work.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] Some implementations emulate the expected behaviour for this special case by extension of the language.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] Before revision, the programmer could decide to have the arguments of a procedure evaluated serially instead of collaterally by using semicolons instead of commas (*gomma*s).
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] then the compiler could evaluate the arguments in whatever order it felt like.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] So far, partial parametrisation has been implemented in Algol 68 Genie, and a subset of the Modules and Separated Compilation facility has been implemented in GCC.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] The S3 language that was used to write the ICL VME operating system and much other system software on the ICL 2900 Series was a direct derivative of ALGOL 68.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] However, it omitted many of the more complex features, and replaced the basic modes with a set of data types that mapped directly to the 2900 Series hardware architecture.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] ALGOL 68R from RRE was the first ALGOL 68 subset implementation, running on the ICL 1900.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] Based on the original language, the main subset restrictions were *definition before use* and no parallel processing.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] This compiler was popular in UK universities in the 1970s, where many computer science students learnt ALGOL 68 as their first programming language; the compiler was renowned for good error messages.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] ALGOL 68RS(RS) from RSRE was a portable compiler system written in ALGOL 68RS (bootstrapped from ALGOL 68R), and implemented on a variety of systems including the ICL 2900/Series 39, Multics and DEC VAX/VMS.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] The language was based on the Revised Report, but with similar subset restrictions to ALGOL 68R.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] This compiler survives in the form of an Algol68-to-C compiler.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] In ALGOL 68S(S) from Carnegie Mellon University the power of parallel processing was improved by adding an orthogonal extension, *eventing*.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] Any variable declaration containing keyword **EVENT** made assignments to this variable eligible for parallel evaluation, i.e. the right hand side was made into a procedure which was moved to one of the processors of the C.mmp multiprocessor system.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] Accesses to such variables were delayed after termination of the assignment.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] Cambridge ALGOL 68C(C) was a portable compiler that implemented a subset of ALGOL 68, restricting operator definitions and omitting garbage collection, flexible rows and formatted transput.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] Algol 68 Genie(G) by Marcel van der Veer is an ALGOL 68 implementation for today's computers and operating systems.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] The interpreter implements one extension - Charles Lindsey’s partial parametrization proposal published in 1976, that gives the imperative language Algol 68 a functional sub-language.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] The GNU Compiler Collection's GNU Algol 68 implements several GNU extensions to the language, providing a strict superlanguage of ALGOL 68, as is explicitly allowed by the Revised Report.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] "Despite good intentions, a programmer may violate portability by inadvertently employing a local extension.
[src:algol-family/algol-68-p02] To guard against this, each implementation should provide a PORTCHECK pragmat option.
[src:algol-family/algol-w] Wirth's entry was considered too little of an advance over ALGOL 60, and the more complex entry from Adriaan van Wijngaarden that would later become ALGOL 68 was selected in a highly contentious meeting.
[src:algol-family/algol-w] Wirth later published his version as *A contribution to the development of ALGOL*.
[src:algol-family/algol-w] With a number of small additions, this eventually became ALGOL W.
[src:algol-family/algol-w] Wirth supervised a high-quality implementation for the IBM System/360 at Stanford University that was widely distributed.
[src:algol-family/algol-w] The implementation was written in PL360, an ALGOL-like assembly language designed by Wirth.
[src:algol-family/algol-w] The implementation includes influential debugging and profiling abilities.
[src:algol-family/algol-w] ALGOL W served as the basis for the Pascal language, and the syntax of ALGOL W will be immediately familiar to anyone with Pascal experience.
[src:algol-family/algol-w] The key differences are improvements to record handling in Pascal, and, oddly, the loss of ALGOL W's ability to define the length of an array at runtime, which is one of Pascal's most-complained-about features.
[src:algol-family/algol-w] ALGOL W's syntax is built on a subset of the EBCDIC character encoding set.
[src:algol-family/algol-w] In ALGOL 60, reserved words are distinct lexical items, but in ALGOL W, they are only sequences of characters, and do not need to be stropped.
[src:algol-family/algol-w] Reserved words and identifiers are separated by spaces.
[src:algol-family/algol-w] In these ways, ALGOL W's syntax resembles that of Pascal and later languages.
[src:algol-family/algol-w] The *ALGOL W Language Description* defines ALGOL W in an affix grammar that resembles Backus–Naur form (BNF).
[src:algol-family/algol-w] This formal grammar was a precursor of the Van Wijngaarden grammar.
[src:algol-family/algol-w] This demonstrates ALGOL W's record type facility, including use of the null reference.
[src:algol-family/algol] In the sense that the syntax of most modern languages is "Algol-like", it was arguably more influential than three other high-level programming languages among which it was roughly contemporary: FORTRAN, Lisp, and COBOL.
[src:algol-family/algol] It was designed to avoid some of the perceived problems with FORTRAN and eventually gave rise to many other programming languages, including PL/I, Simula, BCPL, B, Pascal, Ada, and C.
[src:algol-family/algol] ALGOL introduced code blocks and the `begin`...`end` pairs for delimiting them.
[src:algol-family/algol] It was also the first language implementing nested function definitions with lexical scope.
[src:algol-family/algol] Moreover, it was the first programming language to give detailed attention to formal language definition and, through the *Algol 60 Report*, it introduced Backus–Naur form, a principal formal grammar notation for language design.
[src:algol-family/algol] ALGOL 68 is substantially different from ALGOL 60 and was not well received, so reference to "Algol" is generally understood to mean ALGOL 60 and its dialects.
[src:algol-family/algol] ALGOL was developed jointly by a committee of European and American computer scientists in a meeting in 1958 at the Swiss Federal Institute of Technology in Zurich (cf.
[src:algol-family/algol] It specified three different syntaxes: a reference syntax, a publication syntax, and an implementation syntax, syntaxes that permitted it to use different keyword names and conventions for decimal points (commas vs periods) for different languages.
[src:algol-family/algol] John Backus developed the *Backus normal form* method of describing programming languages specifically for ALGOL 58.
[src:algol-family/algol] A significant contribution of the ALGOL 58 Report was to provide standard terms for programming concepts: statement, declaration, type, label, primary, block, and others.
[src:algol-family/algol] In contrast, ALGOL 68 offered an extensive library of *transput* (input/output) facilities.
[src:algol-family/algol] ALGOL 60 allowed for two evaluation strategies for parameter passing: the common call-by-value, and call-by-name.
[src:algol-family/algol] Call-by-name has certain effects in contrast to call-by-reference.
[src:algol-family/algol] Now that every time swap is referenced, it is reevaluated.
[src:algol-family/algol] Say i := 1 and A[i] := 2, so every time swap is referenced it will return the other combination of the values ([1,2], [2,1], [1,2] and so on).
[src:algol-family/algol] ALGOL 68 was defined using a two-level grammar formalism invented by Adriaan van Wijngaarden and which bears his name.
