[src:algol-family/algol] ALGOL 68 implementations used ALGOL 60's approaches to stropping.
[src:algol-family/algol] In ALGOL 68's case tokens with the bold typeface are reserved words, types (modes) or operators.
[src:algol-family/algol] Note: lower (⌊) and upper (⌈) bounds of an array, and array slicing, are directly available to the programmer.
[src:algol-family/algol] The variations and lack of portability of the programs from one implementation to another is easily demonstrated by the classic hello world program.
[src:algol-family/algol] The next three examples are in Burroughs Extended Algol.
[src:algol-family/algol] The first two direct output at the interactive terminal they are run on.
[src:algol-family/algol] The first uses a character array, similar to C.
[src:algol-family/algol] The language allows the array identifier to be used as a pointer to the array, and hence in a REPLACE statement.
