[src:algol-family/algol] Below is a version from Elliott 803 Algol (A104).
[src:algol-family/algol] The standard Elliott 803 used five-hole paper tape and thus only had upper case.
[src:algol-family/algol] The code lacked any quote characters so £ (UK Pound Sign) was used for open quote and ?
[src:algol-family/algol] Special sequences were placed in double quotes (e.g£. £L?? produced a new line on the teleprinter).
[src:algol-family/algol] The open and close quote characters were represented using '(' and ')' and spaces by %.
[src:algol-family/algol] In the language of the "Algol 68 Report" the input/output facilities were collectively called the "Transput".
[src:algol-family/algol] The ALGOLs were conceived at a time when character sets were diverse and evolving rapidly; also, the ALGOLs were defined so that only *uppercase* letters were required.
[src:algol-family/algol] 1960: IFIP – The Algol 60 language and report included several mathematical symbols which are available on modern computers and operating systems, but, unfortunately, were unsupported on most computing systems at the time.
[src:algol-family/algol] 1961 September: ASCII – The ASCII character set, then in an early stage of development, had the \ (Back slash) character added to it in order to support ALGOL's Boolean operators /\ and \/.
[src:algol-family/algol] 1962: ALCOR – This character set included the unusual "᛭" runic cross character for multiplication and the "⏨" Decimal Exponent Symbol for floating point notation.
[src:algol-family/algol] 1964: GOST – The 1964 Soviet standard GOST 10859 allowed the encoding of 4-bit, 5-bit, 6-bit and 7-bit characters in ALGOL.
[src:algol-family/algol] 1968: The "Algol 68 Report" – used extant ALGOL characters, and further adopted →, ↓, ↑, □, ⌊, ⌈, ⎩, ⎧, ○, ⊥, and ¢ characters which can be found on the IBM 2741 keyboard with *typeball* (or *golf ball*) print heads inserted (such as the APL golf ball).
[src:algol-family/algol] These became available in the mid-1960s while ALGOL 68 was being drafted.
[src:algol-family/algol] The report was translated into Russian, German, French, and Bulgarian, and allowed programming in languages with larger character sets, e.g., Cyrillic alphabet of the Soviet BESM-4.
[src:algol-family/algol] All ALGOL's characters are also part of the Unicode standard and most of them are available in several popular fonts.
[src:algol-family/algol] 2009 October: Unicode – The `⏨` (Decimal Exponent Symbol) for floating-point notation was added to Unicode 5.2 for backward compatibility with historic Buran programme ALGOL software.
[src:algol-family/algol] The Burroughs dialects included special Bootstrapping dialects such as ESPOL and NEWP.
[src:algol-family/algol] The latter is still used for Unisys MCP system software.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] In computer science, **Backus–Naur form** or **Pāṇini–Backus Form** (**BNF** or **PBF**, pronounced /ˌbækəs ˈnaʊər/), also known as **Backus normal form**, is a notation system for defining the syntax of programming languages and other formal languages, developed by John Backus and Peter Naur.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] It is a metasyntax for context-free grammars, providing a precise way to outline the rules of a language's structure.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] It has been widely used in official specifications, manuals, and textbooks on programming language theory, as well as to describe document formats, instruction sets, and communication protocols.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] Over time, variations such as extended Backus–Naur form (EBNF) and augmented Backus–Naur form (ABNF) have emerged, building on the original framework with added features.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] BNF specifications outline how symbols are combined to form syntactically valid sequences.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] Each BNF consists of three core components: a set of non-terminal symbols, a set of terminal symbols, and a series of derivation rules.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] Non-terminal symbols represent categories or variables that can be replaced, while terminal symbols are the fixed, literal elements (such as keywords or punctuation) that appear in the final sequence.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] Derivation rules provide the instructions for replacing non-terminal symbols with specific combinations of symbols.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] For example, in the rule `<opt-suffix-part> ::= "Sr." | "Jr." | ""`, the entire line is the derivation rule, "Sr.", "Jr.", and "" (an empty string) are terminal symbols, and `<opt-suffix-part>` is a non-terminal symbol.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] Generating a valid sequence involves starting with a designated start symbol and iteratively applying the derivation rules.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] This process can extend sequences incrementally.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] To allow flexibility, some BNF definitions include an optional "delete" symbol (represented as an empty alternative, e.g., `<item> ::= <thing> |` ), enabling the removal of certain elements while maintaining syntactic validity.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] Note that many things (such as the format of a first-name, apartment number, ZIP-code, and Roman numeral) are left unspecified here.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] If necessary, they may be described using additional BNF rules.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] The concept of using rewriting rules to describe language structure traces back to at least Pāṇini, an ancient Indian Sanskrit grammarian who lived sometime between the 6th and 4th centuries BC.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] His notation for describing Sanskrit word structure is equivalent in power to that of BNF and exhibits many similar properties.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] In Western society, grammar was long regarded as a subject for teaching rather than scientific study; descriptions were informal and targeted at practical usage.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] This perspective shifted in the first half of the 20th century, when linguists such as Leonard Bloomfield and Zellig Harris began attempts to formalize language description, including phrase structure.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] Meanwhile, mathematicians explored related ideas through string rewriting rules as formal logical systems, such as Axel Thue in 1914, Emil Post in the 1920s–40s, and Alan Turing in 1936.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] Noam Chomsky, teaching linguistics to students of information theory at MIT combined linguistics and mathematics, adapting Thue's formalism to describe natural language syntax.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] In 1956, he introduced a clear distinction between generative rules (those of context-free grammars) and transformation rules.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] BNF itself emerged when John Backus, a programming language designer at IBM, proposed a metalanguage of *metalinguistic formulas* to define the syntax of the new programming language IAL, known today as ALGOL 58, in 1959.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] This notation was formalized in the ALGOL 60 report, where Peter Naur named it *Backus normal form* in the committee's 1963 report.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] Whether Backus was directly influenced by Chomsky's work is uncertain.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] Donald Knuth argued in 1964 that BNF should be read as *Backus–Naur form*, as it is "not a normal form in the conventional sense," unlike Chomsky normal form.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] In 1967, Peter Zilahy Ingerman suggested renaming it *Pāṇini Backus form* to acknowledge Pāṇini's earlier, independent development of a similar notation.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] Naur altered Backus's original symbols for ALGOL 60, changing `:≡` to `::=` and the overbarred "or" to `|`, using commonly available characters.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] BNF is very similar to canonical-form Boolean algebra equations (used in logic-circuit design), reflecting Backus's mathematical background as a FORTRAN designer.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] Studies of Boolean algebra were commonly part of a mathematics curriculum, which may have informed Backus's approach.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] Neither Backus nor Naur described the names enclosed in `< >` as non-terminals—Chomsky's terminology was not originally used in describing BNF.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] Naur later called them "classes" in 1961 course materials.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] In the ALGOL 60 report, they were "metalinguistic variables," with other symbols defining the target language.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] Saul Rosen, involved with the Association for Computing Machinery since 1947, contributed to the transition from IAL to ALGOL and edited Communications of the ACM.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] He described BNF as a metalanguage for ALGOL in his 1967 book.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] Early ALGOL manuals from IBM, Honeywell, Burroughs, and Digital Equipment Corporation followed this usage.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] BNF significantly influenced programming language development, notably as the basis for early compiler-compiler systems.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] Irons' "A Syntax Directed Compiler for ALGOL 60" and Brooker and Morris' "A Compiler Building System," which directly utilized BNF.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] This influenced tools like yacc, a widely used parser generator rooted in BNF principles.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] BNF remains one of the oldest computer-related notations still referenced today, though its variants often dominate modern applications.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] Here, `<expr>` can recursively include itself, allowing repeated additions.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] BNF today is one of the oldest computer-related languages still in use.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] The original BNF did not use quotes as shown in `<literal>` rule.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] This assumes that no whitespace is necessary for proper interpretation of the rule.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] `<EOL>` represents the appropriate line-end specifier (in ASCII, carriage-return, line-feed or both depending on the operating system).
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] `<rule-name>` and `<text>` are to be substituted with a declared rule's name/label or literal text, respectively.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] In the U.S. postal address example above, the entire block-quote is a `<syntax>`.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] Each line or unbroken grouping of lines is a rule; for example one rule begins with `<name-part> ::=`.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] The other part of that rule (aside from a line-end) is an expression, which consists of two lists separated by a vertical bar `|`.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] These two lists consists of some terms (three terms and two terms, respectively).
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] Each term in this particular rule is a rule-name.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] There are many variants and extensions of BNF, generally either for the sake of simplicity and succinctness, or to adapt it to a specific application.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] One common feature of many variants is the use of regular expression repetition operators such as `*` and `+`.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] The extended Backus–Naur form (EBNF) is a common one.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] Another common extension is the use of square brackets around optional items.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] Although not present in the original ALGOL 60 report (instead introduced a few years later in IBM's PL/I definition), the notation is now universally recognised.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] Augmented Backus–Naur form (ABNF) and Routing Backus–Naur form (RBNF) are extensions commonly used to describe Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) protocols.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] Parsing expression grammars build on the BNF and regular expression notations to form an alternative class of formal grammar, which is essentially analytic rather than generative in character.
[src:algol-family/backus-naur-form] Many BNF specifications found online today are intended to be human-readable and are non-formal.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] In computer science, **imperative programming** is a software programming paradigm that provides specific instructions for how computations should take place.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] This paradigm may use statements that may change a process’s state.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] In much the same way that the imperative mood in natural languages expresses commands, an imperative program consists of commands for the computer to perform.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Imperative programming focuses on describing *how* a program operates step by step (the order of the steps being generally determined in source code by the placement of statements one below the other), rather than on high-level descriptions of its expected results.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] The term is often used in contrast to declarative programming, which focuses on *what* the program should accomplish without specifying all the details of *how* the program should achieve the result.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Procedural programming is a type of imperative programming in which the program is built from one or more procedures (also termed subroutines or functions).
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] The terms are often used as synonyms, but the use of procedures has a dramatic effect on how imperative programs appear and how they are constructed.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Heavy procedural programming, in which state changes are localized to procedures or restricted to explicit arguments and returns from procedures, is a form of structured programming.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Since the 1960s, structured programming and modular programming in general have been promoted as techniques to improve the maintainability and overall quality of imperative programs.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] The concepts behind object-oriented programming attempt to extend this approach.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Procedural programming could be considered a step toward declarative programming.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] A programmer can often tell, simply by looking at the names, arguments, and return types of procedures (and related comments), what a particular procedure is supposed to do, without necessarily looking at the details of how it achieves its result.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] At the same time, a complete program is still imperative since it *fixes* the statements to be executed and their order of execution to a large extent.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] The programming paradigm used to build programs for almost all computers typically follows an imperative model.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Digital computer hardware is designed to execute machine code, which is native to the computer and is usually written in the imperative style, although low-level compilers and interpreters using other paradigms exist for some architectures such as Lisp machines.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] From this low-level perspective, the program state is defined by the contents of memory, and the statements are instructions in the native machine language of the computer.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Higher-level imperative languages use variables and more complex statements, but still follow the same paradigm.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Recipes and process checklists, while not computer programs, are also familiar concepts that are similar in style to imperative programming; each step is an instruction, and the physical world holds the state.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Since the basic ideas of imperative programming are both conceptually familiar and directly embodied in the hardware, most computer languages are in the imperative style.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Assignment statements, in imperative paradigm, perform an operation on information located in memory and store the results in memory for later use.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] High-level imperative languages, in addition, permit the evaluation of complex expressions, which may consist of a combination of arithmetic operations and function evaluations, and the assignment of the resulting value to memory.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Looping statements (as in while loops, do while loops, and for loops) allow a sequence of statements to be executed multiple times.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Loops can either execute the statements they contain a predefined number of times, or they can execute them repeatedly until some condition is met.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Conditional branching statements allow a sequence of statements to be executed only if some condition is met.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Otherwise, the statements are skipped and the execution sequence continues from the statement following them.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Unconditional branching statements allow an execution sequence to be transferred to another part of a program.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] These include the jump (called *goto* in many languages), switch, and the subprogram, subroutine, or procedure call (which usually returns to the next statement after the call).
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Early in the development of high-level programming languages, the introduction of the block enabled the construction of programs in which a group of statements and declarations could be treated as if they were one statement.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] This, alongside the introduction of subroutines, enabled complex structures to be expressed by hierarchical decomposition into simpler procedural structures.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] The earliest imperative languages were the machine languages of the original computers.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] In these languages, instructions were very simple, which made hardware implementation easier but hindered the creation of complex programs.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Fortran, developed by John Backus at International Business Machines (IBM) starting in 1954, was the first major programming language to remove the obstacles presented by machine code in the creation of complex programs.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Fortran was a compiled language that allowed named variables, complex expressions, subprograms, and many other features now common in imperative languages.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] The next two decades saw the development of many other major high-level imperative programming languages.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] In the late 1950s and 1960s, ALGOL was developed in order to allow mathematical algorithms to be more easily expressed and even served as the operating system's target language for some computers.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] MUMPS (1966) carried the imperative paradigm to a logical extreme, by not having any statements at all, relying purely on commands, even to the extent of making the IF and ELSE commands independent of each other, connected only by an intrinsic variable named $TEST.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] COBOL (1960) and BASIC (1964) were both attempts to make programming syntax look more like English.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] In the 1970s, Pascal was developed by Niklaus Wirth, and C was created by Dennis Ritchie while he was working at Bell Laboratories.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Wirth went on to design Modula-2 and Oberon.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] For the needs of the United States Department of Defense, Jean Ichbiah and a team at Honeywell began designing Ada in 1978, after a 4-year project to define the requirements for the language.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] The specification was first published in 1983, with revisions in 1995, 2005, and 2012.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] The 1980s saw a rapid growth in interest in object-oriented programming.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] These languages were imperative in style, but added features to support objects.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] The last two decades of the 20th century saw the development of many such languages.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Smalltalk-80, originally conceived by Alan Kay in 1969, was released in 1980, by the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (PARC).
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Drawing from concepts in another object-oriented language—Simula (which is considered the world's first object-oriented programming language, developed in the 1960s)—Bjarne Stroustrup designed C++, an object-oriented language based on C.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Design of C++ began in 1979 and the first implementation was completed in 1983.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Microsoft's .NET Framework (2002) is imperative at its core, as are its main target languages, VB.NET and C# that run on it; however Microsoft's F#, a functional language, also runs on it.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Fortran (1958) was unveiled as "The IBM Mathematical FORmula TRANslating system." It was designed for scientific calculations, without string handling facilities.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] However, non-IBM vendors also wrote Fortran compilers, but with a syntax that would likely fail IBM's compiler.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] The American National Standards Institute (ANSI) developed the first Fortran standard in 1966.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] In 1978, Fortran 77 became the standard until 1991.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] COBOL (1959) stands for "COmmon Business Oriented Language." Fortran manipulated symbols.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] It was soon realized that symbols did not need to be numbers, so strings were introduced.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] The US Department of Defense influenced COBOL's development, with Grace Hopper being a major contributor.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] The statements were English-like and verbose.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] The goal was to design a language so managers could read the programs.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] However, the lack of structured statements hindered this goal.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Development of COBOL was tightly controlled, so dialects did not emerge to require ANSI standards.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] As a consequence, it was not changed for 15 years until 1974.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] The 1990s version did make consequential changes, like object-oriented programming.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] ALGOL (1960) stands for "ALGOrithmic Language." It had a profound influence on programming language design.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Emerging from a committee of European and American programming language experts, it used standard mathematical notation and had a readable structured design.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] ALGOL was first to define its syntax using the Backus–Naur form.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] ALGOL's direct descendants include Pascal, Modula-2, Ada, Delphi and Oberon on one branch.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] On another branch there's C, C++ and Java.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] BASIC (1964) stands for "Beginner's All Purpose Symbolic Instruction Code." It was developed at Dartmouth College for all of their students to learn.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] If a student did not go on to a more powerful language, the student would still remember BASIC.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] A BASIC interpreter was installed in the microcomputers manufactured in the late 1970s.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] As the microcomputer industry grew, so did the language.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] BASIC pioneered the interactive session.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] However, the BASIC syntax was too simple for large programs.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Recent dialects added structure and object-oriented extensions.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Microsoft's Visual Basic is still widely used and produces a graphical user interface.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] C programming language (1973) got its name because the language BCPL was replaced with B, and AT&T Bell Labs called the next version "C." Its purpose was to write the UNIX operating system.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] C is a relatively small language -- making it easy to write compilers.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Its growth mirrored the hardware growth in the 1980s.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Its growth also was because it has the facilities of assembly language, but uses a high-level syntax.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] In the 1970s, software engineers needed language support to break large projects down into modules.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] One obvious feature was to decompose large projects *physically* into separate files.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] A less obvious feature was to decompose large projects *logically* into abstract datatypes.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] At the time, languages supported concrete (scalar) datatypes like integer numbers, floating-point numbers, and strings of characters.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Concrete datatypes have their representation as part of their name.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] Abstract datatypes are structures of concrete datatypes — with a new name assigned.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] For example, a list of integers could be called `integer_list`.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] In object-oriented jargon, abstract datatypes are called classes.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] However, a *class* is only a definition; no memory is allocated.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] When memory is allocated to a class, it's called an object.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] C++ (1985) was originally called "C with Classes." It was designed to expand C's capabilities by adding the object-oriented facilities of the language Simula.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] An object-oriented module is composed of two files.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] The definitions file is called the header file.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] A constructor operation is a function with the same name as the class name.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] It is executed when the calling operation executes the `new` statement.
[src:algol-family/imperative-programming] A module's other file is the *source file*.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] McDowell Award in 1967 for the development of FORTRAN.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] He died at his home in Ashland, Oregon on March 17, 2007.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] Backus was born in Philadelphia and grew up in nearby Wilmington, Delaware.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] He studied at The Hill School in Pottstown, Pennsylvania, but he was apparently not a diligent student.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] He entered college at the University of Virginia to study chemistry, but struggled with his classes there, and he was expelled after less than a year for poor attendance.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] He was subsequently conscripted into the U.S.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] Army during World War II, and eventually came to hold the rank of corporal, being put in command of an anti-aircraft battery stationed at Fort Stewart, Georgia.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] After receiving high scores on a military aptitude test, the Army sent him to study engineering at the University of Pittsburgh.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] He later transferred to a pre-medical program at Haverford College.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] During an internship at a hospital, he was diagnosed with a cranial bone tumor, which was successfully removed, and a plate was installed in his head.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] He then moved to the Flower and Fifth Avenue Medical School for medical school, but found it uninteresting and dropped out after nine months.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] He soon underwent a second operation to replace the metal plate in his head with one of his own design, and received an honorable medical discharge from the U.S.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] After moving to New York City he trained initially as a radio technician and became interested in mathematics.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] He graduated from Columbia University with a bachelor's degree in 1949 and a master's degree in 1950, both in mathematics, and joined IBM in 1950.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] During his first three years, he worked on the Selective Sequence Electronic Calculator (SSEC); his first major project was to write a program to calculate positions of the Moon.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] In 1953, Backus developed the language Speedcoding, the first high-level language created for an IBM computer, to aid in software development for the IBM 701 computer.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] Programming was very difficult at this time, and in 1954 Backus assembled a team to define and develop Fortran for the IBM 704 computer.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] Fortran was the first high-level programming language to be put to broad use.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] This widely used language made computers practical and accessible machines for scientists and others without requiring them to have deep knowledge of the machinery.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] Backus served on the international committees that developed ALGOL 58 and the very influential ALGOL 60, which quickly became the *de facto* worldwide standard for publishing algorithms.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] Backus developed the Backus–Naur form (BNF), published in the UNESCO report on ALGOL 58.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] It was a formal notation able to describe any context-free programming language, and was important in the development of compilers.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] A few deviations from this approach were tried (notably in Lisp and APL), but by the 1970s, Backus–Naur context-free specifications for computer languages had become quite standard, following the development of automated compiler generators such as yacc.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] This contribution helped Backus win the ACM Turing Award in 1977.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] Backus later worked on a function-level programming language known as FP, which he described in his Turing Award lecture "Can Programming be Liberated from the von Neumann Style?".
[src:algol-family/john-backus] Sometimes viewed as Backus's apology for creating Fortran, this paper did less to garner interest in the FP language than to spark research into functional programming in general.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] When Backus publicized the function-level style of programming, his message was mostly misunderstood as being the same as traditional functional programming style languages.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] Iverson's APL, even using a non-standard character set.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] An FP interpreter was distributed with the 4.2BSD Unix operating system, but there were relatively few implementations of the language, most of which were used for educational purposes.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] Backus spent the latter part of his career developing FL (from "Function Level"), a successor to FP.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] FL was an internal IBM research project, and development of the language stopped when the project was finished.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] Only a few papers documenting it remain, and the source code of the compiler described in them was not made public.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] FL was at odds with functional programming languages being developed in the 1980s, most of which were based on the lambda calculus and static typing systems instead of, as in APL, the concatenation of primitive operations.
[src:algol-family/john-backus] Many of the language's ideas have now been implemented in versions of the J programming language, Iverson's successor to APL.
